# ğŸ“ 3. Detailed Explanation of All Layers (Server-Based)

---

#  3.1 Internet-Facing Layer

### Public DNS

Maps domain â†’ public LB IP:

 `api.myshop.com` â†’ 3.12.10.5 (Load Balancer)

### CDN

 Caches static content
 Reduces backend load

### WAF + DDoS

 Blocks SQL injection, XSS
 Filters bots
 Mitigates large DDoS attacks

### Public Load Balancer

 Checks server health
 Routes traffic to Nginx reverse proxy

### Nginx/HAProxy Reverse Proxy

 Terminates SSL
 Routes traffic based on path:

   `/api/order â†’ Order server`
   `/api/payment â†’ Payment server`

---

#  3.2 Application Layer â€” Running on LINUX SERVERS (No Kubernetes)

Each microservice runs as a systemd service on a dedicated Linux VM.

Example:

```
[Unit]
Description=Order Service
After=network.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/order-service
Restart=always
User=appuser

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

Microservices:

### Order Service

 Handles order creation
 Validates products
 Stores in DB

### Payment Service

 Calls payment gateway
 Updates payment status

### Inventory Service

 Checks and updates stock

### Notification Service

 Email/SMS/Push

Every service has:

 Logs in `/var/log/app`
 Nginx upstream configuration
 FirewallD rules
 Node health checks

---

#  3.3 Internal Server-to-Server Communication

Internal services must talk to each other:

 Order â†’ DB
 Payment â†’ Kafka
 Workers â†’ SAP Ariba

Linux firewall rules ensure only allowed ports work.

Example:

```
firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=8081/tcp
firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=5432/tcp
firewall-cmd --reload
```

---

#  3.4 Message Queue Layer (Kafka / RabbitMQ)

Kafka servers run on Linux machines:

 `kafka01.internal`
 `kafka02.internal`

Used for:

 Payment events
 Order dispatched events
 Inventory updates

Workers subscribe to topics and process jobs.

---

#  3.5 Background Worker Servers

Worker servers:

 Pull tasks from Kafka
 Process payments
 Export data to SAP Ariba
 Send notification emails/SMS
 Update order lifecycle

Run as systemd or cron jobs.

---

#  3.6 Database Cluster

Replicated Postgres/MySQL setup:

 Primary DB server
 Replica DB servers
 Auto failover using scripts or PgPool-II

Backups:

 Daily full backup
 WAL log archiving

Monitoring:

 Slow queries
 Replication lag
 Connection count

---

#  3.7 External Enterprise Integration â€“ SAP Ariba

 Worker servers call SAP Ariba REST APIs
 Uses OAuth2 tokens
 Handles retries & failures
 Full audit logs stored in DB

---

#  3.8 Monitoring, Logging & Alerting

### Prometheus Node Exporter

Monitors:

 CPU
 Memory
 Disk
 I/O
 Network
 Service health

### Grafana

Dashboards for:

 API latency
 Requests per second
 DB stats
 Kafka queue depth

### ELK / Loki Logs

 Nginx logs
 App logs
 Worker logs
 OS logs

### Alerting

Triggered when:

 API error rate > threshold
 Disk > 80%
 DB replication lag
 High load average
 Node down

---

#  3.9 CI/CD Deployment Pipeline

### Tools:

 GitHub Actions / Jenkins
 Bash scripts
 Ansible + SSH
 Artifactory/Nexus registry

Pipeline flow:

1. Developer pushes code
2. CI builds package
3. Runs tests
4. Creates versioned artifact
5. Deploys to server via Ansible
6. Restarts systemd service
7. Performs health checks

---

